##Aerosol transmission of new coronavirus? Important, but no need to panic

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

On February 8, at a news conference held by the Shanghai Municipal Leading Group on Epidemic Prevention and control, Zeng Qun, deputy director of the Shanghai Civil Affairs Bureau, said that, at present, the main routes of transmission of NCP are direct transmission, aerosol transmission and contact transmission.
"Aerosol Transmission" has been identified as one of the routes of transmission of new coronary pneumonia, causing a heated debate. Just three days ago, the National Health Commission's website published the diagnosis and treatment plan for COVID-19 pneumonia (trial version 5) , which described the route of transmission of the virus, a new expression was added on the basis of "respiratory droplets and contact transmission are the main transmission routes" , and it was still very cautious at that time as "Aerosol and alimentary tract transmission routes are yet to be defined" .
WHAT DOES AEROSOL TRANSPORT MEAN? Will new coronary pneumonia catch you off guard? This newspaper interviewed Cao Junji, a researcher at the Institute of Earth Environment of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Director of the key laboratory of Aerosol Chemistry and Physics of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and secretary-general of the International Aerosol Society, wang Minghuai, a professor at the Nanjing University and Chairman of the Department of Atmospheric Physics, and Li Dong, deputy director of the infection center at Youan Hospital in Beijing. On the one hand, they agree that COVID-19 is likely to spread through aerosols; on the other, they warn that precautions should be taken without creating too much panic.

On the one hand, they agree that COVID-19 is likely to spread through aerosols; on the other, they warn that precautions should be taken without creating too much panic.

Reporter | Wang Zihui, Yan Yan

Evidence of Aerosol transmission of the new coronavirus?

Sanlian Life Weekly: At the news conference of Shanghai Epidemic Prevention and Control Leading Group, Aerosol transmission is one of the transmission ways of new coronary pneumonia. In your professional opinion, is it possible to determine whether the new coronavirus can be transmitted by Aerosol?

Cao Junji: First of all, the content of the press conference was relatively brief and did not give much explanation on how this conclusion was reached. But that's not a very accurate statement. Because the COVID-19 has been out there for more than a month, there's not enough data to confirm it, and it's very difficult to do accurate research at the moment.

Personally, I don't think it's a big deal from a management point of view, but from an academic point of view, it's not conclusive, it's just highly probable.

Sanlian Life Weekly: from the current data, do you find some evidence of transmission of the new coronavirus through aerosol?

Cao Junji: At present, most of the reported cases in China are related to patients, but the risk of aerosol infection is still high. For example, I looked specifically at the data of Shaanxi Province. Most of the cases in Shaanxi Province are imported cases. However, since February 1, there have been 11 cases in Shaanxi with no obvious history of exposure, which has increased to 11 cases by February 8, we must pay close attention to this development. In cases with no apparent history of contact, epidemiological investigations can not find out with which patients the person has a history of apparent contact, which means it is very likely that he is not transmitted through contact or direct transmission, so it's spread by Aerosol. At present, the proportion of cases of local spread of the case is relatively low, but there is no small risk, so we should draw special attention to the spread of Aerosol hazards.

Image | shutterstock

Sanlian Life Weekly: Are Possible Aerosol transmission channels unique to the new coronavirus?

Cao Junji: Looking back, researchers have found clear evidence that the SARS virus traveled through Aerosol routes. In 2004, Hong Kong, China scholar Yu et Al. . A study of the distribution of cases in Amoy Gardens in Hong Kong during the SARS outbreak has found that the SARS virus may have spread through the air, according to a paper published in the Journal The New England Journal of Medicine. At that time, more than 300 people in Amoy Gardens in Hong Kong were infected with the SARS virus. Researchers investigated the presence of the virus in the ventilation shafts of buildings and used the computational fluid dynamics method to estimate the dispersion of the virus-containing Aerosol from the ventilation shafts among buildings, it was found that the calculated aerosol distribution was in good agreement with the actual case distribution, and it was inferred that SARS might be transmitted by air.

Although there are not many studies because of the difficulty in recovering from the scene and in testing the virus in the environment, experience suggests that many respiratory disease viruses do have aerosol routes of transmission. So in theory, the new coronavirus and the SARS virus, there is also a very great possibility of transmission through the Aerosol route.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sanlian Life Weekly: Before the new coronavirus is also considered to have the characteristics of faecal-oral transmission, whether this is also related to aerosol transmission?

Cao Junji: strictly speaking, I think the new coronavirus, even if there is faecal transmission, is not an important way. Why? Because faecal-oral transmission is mainly directed against the digestive tract virus, such as excrement into sewage, was exposed to the infection, but it is still a contact.

On the other hand, faecal-oral transmission is carried by Aerosol agents, as in the case of Amoy Gardens in Hong Kong, where the waste is discharged into the sewers, where the sewage is dried or atomized and becomes a viral aerosol, and then inhaled into people's homes, causing people to inhale and become infected. To eliminate this possibility, it is necessary to strengthen the management of medical waste, including patients'feces, urine, vomit to clean up to prevent infection through aerosol route.

HOW DOES AEROSOL TRAVEL?

Sanlian Life Weekly: What Is Aerosol? How did it come about?

Wang: Aerosols are small particles of liquid or solid suspended in the air. PM2.5 particles, as they are known, are actually a class of aerosol particles.

Cao Junji: actually, all of US expel Aerosol from breathing to talking, singing and sneezing all the time, which comes from basic physiological activities. A sneeze can produce as many as 40,000 droplets between 0.5 and 12 microns in diameter and can be expelled at speeds of up to 100 meters per second; a cough can produce up to 3,000 droplets, about the same amount of droplets as a five minute conversation. The larger particles tend to settle to the surface, while the smaller particles are likely to produce infectious aerosols. A 2009 World Health Organization report noted that viruses or bacteria can travel long distances through aerosols and cause large-scale infections in a short time.

Sanlian Life Weekly: So, what's the difference between "Aerosol" and "Foam" ?

Cao Junji: The main difference between Aerosol and foam is the particle size, which is the particle size. For example, when we speak or sneeze, the droplets that are often visible to the naked eye are millimetres in diameter. Aerosols, on the other hand, are small particles of liquid or solid, usually less than 100 microns (0.1 millimetres) , that are suspended in the air.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Red Color is aerosol, and the green color is spray

In a typical indoor environment, droplets larger than 100 microns usually fall to the surface before evaporating, while particles smaller than 100 microns evaporate before reaching the surface to form droplets, droplets of up to 10 microns can form in milliseconds. Particles of this magnitude don't fall out of the air, because they have very little gravity, and they're suspended in the air, and as the air moves around, it pollutes the air, and that's the problem. The average lifetime of an aerosol is a week, with some length and some length, and an average of seven days. For seven days, it will float in the air and not sink.

In addition, the distances of the two kinds of propagation are different. Because of its particle size is generally 1 to 5 mm, generally in the source of infection 1 to 2 meters of space spread, is short-range transmission. Aerosol particles are generally 0.1 mm or less in diameter and travel hundreds of meters in the air, increasing the risk of non-contact transmission.

Wang: Because Aerosol particles are much smaller, it is difficult for Aerosol particles to fall to the ground as quickly as droplets, and stay in the atmosphere for a longer time, so they also travel farther. For example, a drop of 3 meters would take 10 seconds for a particle of 100 microns, an hour for a particle of 5 microns, and less than 3 microns would be suspended in the atmosphere, making it difficult to settle to the surface in a short time.

Sanlian Life Weekly: under what circumstances is it easiest to contract the virus through Aerosol?

The Aerosol itself is not a novel route, Li Dong said. It is present in many infectious diseases, but the conditions for its formation are harsh. A sneeze can produce droplets or aerosols, but in an open area, they are difficult to spread. People are most likely to be infected: In a closed environment, there is a large number of virus release. For example, in an elevator, a patient coughs, and as soon as he leaves the elevator, you walk in without a mask, and you get an infection, which is transmitted by Aerosol.

Cao Junji: the spread of the virus aerosol is mainly in enclosed and semi-enclosed spaces, streets and other open spaces generally no problem. This is because, first, the virus aerosol in the air will be "inactivated. ". Viruses are more likely to die when they leave body fluids and drift through the air. And there are ultraviolet rays in the air, and there are free radicals, which are highly oxidizing substances, that can kill viruses, or make them less toxic, and that's one thing. Second, in an open space, even if someone expels a lot of the virus in one breath, it can easily be diluted in the air and the concentration of the virus can be reduced to a safe level. Therefore, regular ventilation in confined spaces is important, which was clearly stated in the WHO 2009 report as an important measure to reduce the risk of infection.

How to prevent the spread of Aerosol?

"Sanlian Life Weekly" : Aerosol Life Cycle is long, long transmission distance, does it mean that the threat of Aerosol transmission is very big?

Li Dong: There's no need to panic about the spread of aerosols. The farther away you are, the more diluted by the air. We spit in the Yangtze River, for example, and eventually, it all goes out to sea, so it doesn't make much of a difference, so I stress that the conditions for an aerosol infection are quite harsh.

Cao Junji: the possibility of Aerosol transmission does exist, but the threat is not too great. This is because, first, the concentration of Aerosol transport is very low. It doesn't spread like contact, like an elevator button, just by touching it with your hand. In the General Open Environment, the concentration of the aerosol itself is very low. Second, the probability of Aerosol propagation is very low. In a less enclosed space, there is little chance that the virus will be inhaled once it has been released.

So you don't have to panic, but you do have to take personal precautions. Emphasize the possibility of Aerosol Transmission, is to remind everyone, do not think not to contact it will be fine, not contact is also possible to be infected.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sanlian Life Weekly: For the spread of Aerosol, how should individuals protect themselves?

Cao Junji: The problem of Aerosol spread mainly appears in the enclosed or semi-enclosed space, the open space is OK, we do not have to blindly panic, that the current ambient air is filled with viruses.

First, you want to minimize your exposure to the virus. For example, go outside strange places, be sure to do a good job of personal protection, go out when try to wear a mask.

Second, to prevent possible transmission by others. Contact with outsiders must wear a mask, as far as possible do not go to the gathering place, especially closed and semi-closed ventilation poor space.

Third, guard against the presence of viruses. In closed spaces such as homes and offices, as many ways as possible should be used to kill the virus or reduce the concentration of the virus: including the use of such as alcohol, disinfectants, ultraviolet lamps, sterilizers and other active killing of new viruses, reduce the chance of survival; also watch for natural ventilation, or use air purifier, to reduce the possible concentration of the virus.
